  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 20.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And they had no power.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Literally, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "no hands. Our",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " version here follows the Arabic, Syriac, and Chaldee versions. The LXX. and Vulgate render no ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "direction",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " in which to fly. But in this case ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "לָהֶם",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " would seem preferable to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "בָהֶם",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The Vulgate translates the last clause of the verse, \"Praesertim cum hi, qui simulaverint fugam...  fortissime restitissent.\" They could not flee back to the city, for it was in flames. They could not advance northward, because the Israelites had faced about and were coming to meet them. To flee in any other direction would be to cut off the last hope of saving the city. For ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "יָד",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " in the sense of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "side",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "direction",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", however, see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 2:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 2:37",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and especially the dual, as here, in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 34:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
